\noindent
{\bf Adiabatic dynamics plays an essential role in quantum technologies \cite{Farhi01,CZ12,ZR99,An14}. By driving a quantum system slowly, the quantum evolution can be engineered with suppressed excitation. Yet, environmentally-induced decoherence limits the implementation of adiabatic protocols. Shortcuts to adiabaticity (STA) have the potential to revolutionize quantum technologies by speeding up the time evolution while mimicking adiabatic dynamics. These nonadiabatic protocols can be  engineered by means an auxiliary control field is used to tailor excitations  \cite{Bason12,Zhang13}.  Here we present the first experimental realization of counterdiabatic driving  \cite{Rice03,Berry09}  in a continuous variable system, implementing a shortcut to the adiabatic transport of a trapped ion, in which nonadiabatic transitions are suppressed during all stages of the process. The resulting dynamics is equivalent to a ``fast-motion video'' of the adiabatic trajectory. We experimentally demonstrate the enhanced robustness of the protocol with respect to alternative approaches based on classical local controls \cite{MN10,Torrontegui11} including Fourier optimization schemes \cite{Odelin14}. Our results demonstrate that STA protocols provide a robust speedup on demand, paving the way to their application in a wide variety of quantum technologies \cite{Zhang14,Kielpinski02,Deng13,delcampo14,SS15,SSS15}.
}
\\\\
\indent According to the adiabatic theorem, a system prepared in a non-degenerate eigenstate will remain in the instantaneous eigenstate during its time evolution under the requirement of slow driving. By contrast, the breakdown of adiabatic dynamics under fast driving couples different energy modes and induces nonadiabatic transitions. Nonadiabatic excitations can however be tailored using shortcuts to adiabaticity (STA) to mimic adiabatic dynamics. Among the available techniques to engineer STA \cite{Torrontegui13}, counterdiabatic driving (CD), relies on the use of an auxiliary control $\hat{H}_{\rm CD}$ to explicitly suppress transitions between different energy eigenstates and enforce parallel transport \cite{Rice03,Berry09}.

\indent The transport can be realized by applying a time dependent force $f(t)$ to a particle of mass $m$ in a harmonic oscillator of frequency $\omega$, described by

nexttext:
where $x_{0}=\sqrt{1/2m\omega}$, $f(t) = \Omega(t)\Delta k/2$, $\Omega(t)$ is proportional to the intensity of both Raman beams, $\Delta k$ is the projection of the wave-vectors difference of the Raman beams on the motional axis of the ion and $\phi$ is the phase difference between those two laser beams. Both laser beams are red detuned from the transition between the ground state $\mbox{$\left| {g} \right>$}=\mbox{$\left| {F=0,m_{F}=0} \right>$}\ ({^2}{S}{_{1/2}})$ and the excited state $\mbox{$\left| {e} \right>$}=\mbox{$\left| {F=1,m_{F}=1} \right>$}\, ({^2}{P}{_{1/2}})$. Due to the large detuning $\Delta\approx 2\pi\times14{\,\mbox{{THz}}}$, the excited state $\mbox{$\left| {e} \right>$}$ is adiabatically eliminated. The effective trap frequency $\omega=2\pi \times 20$ kHz in the interaction frame comes from the difference between the beat-note frequency of the laser beams $\delta$ and the real trap frequency $\nu=2\pi\times3.1{\,\mbox{{MHz}}}$. The effective mass is given by $m=\frac{\nu}{\omega}M_{\rm Yb}$ ($M_{\rm Yb}$: mass of {\mbox{$^{{{171}}}${Yb}$^+$}}). When the phase $\phi=0$, the Hamiltonian (\ref{Heff}) describes a dragged harmonic oscillator, with the dragging term $f(t)\hat{x}$. We can implement the CD term  $h(t)\hat{p}$, where $h(t)=-\frac{\dot{f}(t)}{m\omega^{2}}$, by setting $\phi=-\pi/2$ (see section A of the supplementary information for further detailed description of the system). \\

\begin{figure}[!t]
\begin{center}
\includegraphics[width=0.85\onecolfig]{EL}
\end{center}
\caption{\textbf{The scheme of the dragged harmonic oscillator model realized with a trapped {\mbox{$^{{{171}}}${Yb}$^+$}}} (energy levels not to scale).
A pair of counter-propagating Raman laser beams with beat note $\delta$ form a moving standing wave, which is used to manipulate the motion of the ion. The Raman beams are detuned by $\Delta\approx 2\pi\times14{\,\mbox{{THz}}}$ from the transition between the ground state $\mbox{$\left| {g} \right>$}$ and the exited state $\mbox{$\left| {e} \right>$}$. The beat note $\delta$ is smaller than the transverse mode frequency $\nu=2\pi\times3.1{\,\mbox{{MHz}}}$ by $\omega=2\pi\times 20{\,\mbox{{kHz}}}$. $\vec{k}_{\rm r}\ (\vec{k}_{\rm b})$, $\phi_{\rm r}\ (\phi_{\rm b})$ and $g_{\rm r}\ (g_{\rm b})$ are the wave vector, phase and the dipole interaction of the lower (higher) frequency beam (see the section A of the supplementary information). By varying the intensity and the phase of the Raman beams, we can control the direction and strength of the displacement of the ion in the phase space.}
\label{EL}
\end{figure}


\indent In the experiment, after Doppler and motional sideband cooling, $\mbox{$\left| {g} \right>$}$ is prepared with about $0.02\pm 0.02$ average phonon number. Because we can not measure the phonon distribution in the interaction picture directly, the STA performance  is probed using a quench echo experiment \cite{QZ10} in which the ion is first transported adiabatically and then brought back to the initial location using the STA protocol. During the first adiabatic process, we linearly increase the force $f(t)$ from $0$ to  $f_{\rm max}=\Omega_{\rm max}\Delta k/2$ within one period of the harmonic motion $T_{0}=2\pi/\omega=50{\,\mbox{{$\mu$s}}}$, where $\Omega_{\rm max}=2\pi\times378{\,\mbox{{kHz}}}$ corresponds to the maximum value allowed by the laser. This linear ramp has been well studied in experiments \cite{Couvert08,Bowler12,An14} and can be regarded as perfectly adiabatic. Following it, the force is linearly reduced from $f_{\rm max}$ to $0$ within a duration of $sT_{0}$, where $s$ is defined as the shortcut ratio. The backward dynamics is assisted by turning on the laser to implement the CD term $h(t)\hat{p}$ according to Eq.\ (\ref{HCDT}). The relation between the strength of the CD term and the shortcut ratio is given by $h(t)\equiv h_{\rm max}/(2\pi s)$ and the minimum shortcut ratio $s_{\rm min}=1/2\pi$ is achieved by the maximum value of $h(t)= h_{\rm max}$. Finally, we apply blue sideband transitions to measure the phonon distribution \cite{Leibfried03}. The time-dependent laser intensity profiles (waveforms) during the forward and backward transport stages are showed in Fig.\ \ref{Wav}. We vary $s$ from $0.95$ to $0.15$ with a step of 0.1 and we do not observe any noticeable excitation for all shortcut ratios. We obtain the final average phonon number $0.016\pm 0.018$, which confirms that the CD protocol does not excite the motion after the transport, regardless of  $s$ (see section B and C of the supplementary information for the detailed procedure and more data.). \\

\begin{figure}[!t]
\begin{center}
\includegraphics[width=0.85\onecolfig]{wavf}
\end{center}
\caption{\textbf{Time-dependent control fields for different STAs.} In order to measure the phonon excitation after a shortcut, we first use a linear ramp within one period of the harmonic oscillation $2\pi/\omega=50{\,\mbox{{$\mu$s}}}$. Then we apply different shortcut protocols to bring the ion back to its original location. The force $f(t)$ is increased or decreased by changing the intensity of Raman laser beams with $\phi=0$. The function $h(t)$ represents the strength of the CD term proportional to the momentum, which is implemented by applying the laser beams with $\phi=-\pi/2$ during the backward transport. The $f_{\rm max}$ and $h_{\rm max}$ are the maximum values allowed by the common maximum intensity of the laser beams. The smallest shortcut ratio is limited by the maximum laser intensity and we choose the value $s=0.4$ for the CD and UE transport and $s=1.5$ for the Fourier optimization scheme of degree $N=3$.}
\label{Wav}
\end{figure}


